summaries.title: Summary 290.1
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah described how leading senior design teams strengthened her confidence in project management and technical problem-solving. She reflected on mentorship as a core component of her academic identity, often supporting younger women of color navigating engineering culture. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Summary 290.2
summaries.summaryText: Daniel expressed pride in representing his family’s aspirations but also noted ongoing struggles with imposter syndrome. He values belonging through peer groups that normalize his experiences as a first-gen student of color in STEM. [Part 1/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Completed internship at a manufacturing firm where he recognized gender imbalance in leadership positions. [Timeline 4]
Struggled during his first programming course, leading him to seek help from tutoring and peers. [Timeline 3]
Presented senior capstone project on sustainable urban drainage systems, earning department recognition. [Timeline 1]
Presented research poster at a regional engineering conference, receiving recognition from faculty mentors. [Timeline 1]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Family Expectations and Cultural Motivation
themes.description: Cultural values around family honor and sacrifice serve both as motivation and a source of pressure for first-generation Vietnamese-American students pursuing STEM. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyah’s mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 1]

quotes.quoteText: Mentorship is how we survive here — sharing what we’ve learned keeps us going when the system doesn’t always see us. [Context 1]
I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 3]
My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 4]
I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship — it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 1]
If I can use my position to make sure everyone gets a fair shot in our projects, that’s what good leadership looks like. [Context 1]
